ENTRY            D1080   20251103   20260508   20260508       D151
SUBENT        D1080001   20251103   20260508   20260508       D151
BIB                  9         26
TITLE      alpha-induced neutron emission from 27Al:
            A cross-section study
AUTHOR     (R.Roy, D.A.Testov, D.L.Balabanski, M.Kaur, A.Kusoglu,
            G.Lorusso, S.Singh, P.-A.Soederstroem, Y.Xu, S.Aogaki,
            S-R.Ban, M.Brezeanu, I.Burducea, R.Corbu, M.Cuciuc,
            A.Dhal, N.Djourelov, N.Florea, A.Gavrilescu,
            C.Gheorghiu, G.L.Guardo, D.Iancu, V.Lelasseux,
            C.V.Nedelcu, H.Pai, P.Parlea, T.Petruse, A.Rotaru,
            A.N.State, M.Straticiuc, V.Toma, T.Tozar,
            D.Choudhury)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,112,044613,2025)
INSTITUTE  (3INDIIR,2TUKSTU,2UK NPL,2UK SUR,3RUMBUC,2ITYLNS)
           (3RUMRUM) Extreme Light Infrastructure - Nuclear
            Physics, Magurele
FACILITY   (VDGT,3RUMBUC) 3-MV Tandetron
SAMPLE     Two samples were irradiated:
           - 27Al (20 ug/cm2) evaporated on Ta backing (65 ug/cm2)
            irradiated at E=2.5-5.2 MeV in step of 10 keV
           - 27Al (63 ug/cm2) irradiated at a few energies in
            3.4-5.2 MeV
DETECTOR   (HE3SP) 28 helium-3 proportional counters (ELEGANT-TN)
            arranged in three concentric rings positioned at
            5.9 cm (inner ring), 13 cm (middle ring) and 15.5 cm
            (outer ring) from the beam axis.
STATUS     (APRVD) Proofread by Rajat Roy (2025-11-11)
HISTORY    (20251103C) On
ENDBIB              26
NOCOMMON             0          0
ENDSUBENT           29
SUBENT        D1080002   20251103   20260508   20260508       D151
BIB                  4          8
REACTION   (13-AL-27(A,N)15-P-30,,SIG)
INC-SPECT  (EN-RSL-HW) Energy loss
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-T) Uncertainties (~10%) due to
                       counting statistics (typically below 2%)
           (ERR-1)     neutron detection efficiency        (8%)
           (ERR-2)     target thickness                    (5%)
           (ERR-3,,1.) number of incident alpha particles (<1%)
